Cicero has started an ironical cavil at the dispensations of Nature z ‘ It is very hard that, whereas in bodily diseases the more serious the complaint the more competent is the physician called in, in trials, where a man’s civil existence is in jeopardy, the more serious the indictment the more incompetent is the advocate retained.' So far there is nothing to show that Cicero is not in earnest ; but the opening words of the following clause (1πί,τὶ forte), with their ten- tative solntion of the difficulty (which involves its real explanation), make it impossible to mistake the banter of the passage, which is aimed of course at the unfortunate Caepasius—‘but perhaps the reason is that doctors have only to supply skill, advocates both skill and moral support (and the latter only a low-class advocate will give to a shady case).'
